      <slide>
        <title>Remark 3.2.1 </title>
        <p original-id="AT2-s3r2s1p1" internal-id="p-AT2-c-b-a-a">
Recall that a linear map <m original-id="AT2-s3r2s1p1m1" internal-id="m-AT2-c-b-a-a-a">T:V\rightarrow W</m>
satisfies
    </p>
        <ol original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2" internal-id="ol-AT2-c-b-a-b">
          <li original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l1" internal-id="li-AT2-c-b-a-b-a">
    <p original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l1p1" internal-id="p-AT2-c-b-a-b-a-a">
    <m original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l1p1m1" internal-id="m-AT2-c-b-a-b-a-a-a">T(\vec{v}+\vec{w}) = T(\vec{v})+T(\vec{w})</m>
      for any <m original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l1p1m2" internal-id="m-AT2-c-b-a-b-a-a-b">\vec{v},\vec{w} \in V</m>.
    </p>
</li>
          <li original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l2" internal-id="li-AT2-c-b-a-b-b">
    <p original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l2p1" internal-id="p-AT2-c-b-a-b-b-a">
    <m original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l2p1m1" internal-id="m-AT2-c-b-a-b-b-a-a">T(c\vec{v}) = cT(\vec{v})</m>
      for any <m original-id="AT2-s3r2s1o2l2p1m2" internal-id="m-AT2-c-b-a-b-b-a-b">c \in \IR,\vec{v} \in V</m>.
    </p>
</li>
        </ol>
        <p original-id="AT2-s3r2s1p3" internal-id="p-AT2-c-b-a-c">
In other words, a map is linear when vector space operations
can be applied before or after the transformation without affecting the result.
    </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
